[4127.176795, "o", "USERDEL(8)         System Management Commands         USERDEL(8)\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mNAME\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       userdel - delete a user account and related files\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mSYNOPSIS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1muserdel\u001b[0m [options] \u001b[4mLOGIN\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mDESCRIPTION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1muserdel\u001b[0m is a low level utility for removing users. On\u001b[m\r\n       Debian, administrators should usually use \u001b[1mdeluser\u001b[0m(8)\u001b[m\r\n       instead.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       The \u001b[1muserdel\u001b[0m command modifies the system account files,\u001b[m\r\n       deleting all entries that refer to the user name \u001b[4mLOGIN\u001b[24m.\u001b[m\r\n       The named user must exist.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m Manual page userdel(8) line 1 (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
