[4135.026955, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[7mal page userdel(8) line 1/224 7% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[4135.520609, "o", "\r\u001b[K"]
[4135.520982, "o", "\u001b[1mOPTIONS\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The options which apply to the \u001b[1muserdel\u001b[0m command are:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-f\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m--force\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           This option forces the removal of the user account,\u001b[m\r\n           even if the user is still logged in. It also forces\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[1muserdel\u001b[0m to remove the user's home directory and mail\u001b[m\r\n           spool, even if another user uses the same home\u001b[m\r\n           directory or if the mail spool is not owned by the\u001b[m\r\n           specified user. If \u001b[1mUSERGROUPS_ENAB\u001b[0m is defined to \u001b[4myes\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n           in /etc/login.defs and if a group exists with the\u001b[m\r\n           same name as the deleted user, then this group will\u001b[m\r\n           be removed, even if it is still the primary group of\u001b[m\r\n           another user.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           \u001b[4mNote:\u001b[24m This option is dangerous and may leave your\u001b[m\r\n           system in an inconsistent state.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m page userdel(8) line 18/224 17% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[4135.987463, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-h\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m--help\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Display help message and exit.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-r\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m--remove\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Files in the user's home directory will be removed\u001b[m\r\n           along with the home directory itself and the user's\u001b[m\r\n           mail spool. Files located in other file systems will\u001b[m\r\n           have to be searched for and deleted manually.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n           The mail spool is defined by the \u001b[1mMAIL_DIR\u001b[0m variable in\u001b[m\r\n           the login.defs file.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-R\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m--root\u001b[0m \u001b[4mCHROOT_DIR\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n           Apply changes in the \u001b[4mCHROOT_DIR\u001b[24m directory and use the\u001b[m\r\n           configuration files from the \u001b[4mCHROOT_DIR\u001b[24m directory.\u001b[m\r\n           Only absolute paths are supported.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m page userdel(8) line 35/224 25% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
[4136.54964, "o", "\r\u001b[K\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-P\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m--prefix\u001b[0m \u001b[4mPREFIX_DIR\u001b[24m\u001b[m\r\n           Apply changes in the \u001b[4mPREFIX_DIR\u001b[24m directory and use the\u001b[m\r\n           configuration files from the \u001b[4mPREFIX_DIR\u001b[24m directory.\u001b[m\r\n           This option does not chroot and is intended for\u001b[m\r\n           preparing a cross-compilation target. Some\u001b[m\r\n           limitations: NIS and LDAP users/groups are not\u001b[m\r\n           verified. PAM authentication is using the host files.\u001b[m\r\n           No SELINUX support.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n       \u001b[1m-Z\u001b[0m, \u001b[1m--selinux-user\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n           Remove any SELinux user mapping for the user's login.\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[1mCONFIGURATION\u001b[0m\u001b[m\r\n       The following configuration variables in /etc/login.defs\u001b[m\r\n       change the behavior of this tool:\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[m\r\n\u001b[7m page userdel(8) line 52/224 34% (press h for help or q to quit)\u001b[27m\u001b[K"]
